1. Introduction -> 1.2. Relationship to:
{
    "1. Introduction -> 1.2. Relationship to DHCPv4": [
        {
            "Original": "The operational models and relevant configuration information for DHCPv4 [RFC2131] [RFC2132] and DHCPv6 are sufficiently different that integration between the two services is not included in this document.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "[RFC3315\"\")] suggested that future work might be to extend DHCPv6 to carry IPv4 address and configuration information.",
            "Adjusted": "RFC3315 suggested that future work might be to extend DHCPv6 to carry IPv4 address and configuration information."
        },
        {
            "Original": "However, the current consensus of the IETF is that DHCPv4 should be used rather than DHCPv6 when conveying IPv4 configuration information to nodes.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For IPv6-only networks, [RFC7341 Transport\"\")] describes a transport mechanism to carry DHCPv4 messages using the DHCPv6 protocol for the dynamic provisioning of IPv4 address and configuration information.",
            "Adjusted": "For IPv6-only networks, RFC7341 describes a transport mechanism to carry DHCPv4 messages using the DHCPv6 protocol for the dynamic provisioning of IPv4 address and configuration information."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Merging DHCPv4 and DHCPv6 configuration is out of scope for this document.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "[RFC4477: IPv4 and IPv6 Dual-Stack Issues\"\")] discusses some issues and possible strategies for running DHCPv4 and DHCPv6 services together.",
            "Adjusted": "RFC4477 discusses some issues and possible strategies for running DHCPv4 and DHCPv6 services together."
        },
        {
            "Original": "While [RFC4477: IPv4 and IPv6 Dual-Stack Issues\"\")] is a bit dated, it provides a good overview of the issues at hand.",
            "Adjusted": "While RFC4477 is a bit dated, it provides a good overview of the issues at hand."
        }
    ]
}

1. Introduction -> 1.1. Relationship to:
{
    "1.1. Relationship to Previous DHCPv6 Standards": [
        {
            "Original": "The initial specification of DHCPv6 was defined in [RFC3315\"\"], and a number of follow-up documents were published over the years: \\- [RFC3633 version 6\"\"] (\"IPv6 Prefix Options for Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) version 6\") \\- [RFC3736 Service for IPv6\"\"] (\"Stateless Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) Service for IPv6\") \\- [RFC4242\"\"] (\"Information Refresh Time Option for Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol for IPv6 (DHCPv6)\") \\- [RFC7083] (\"Modification to Default Values of SOL_MAX_RT and INF_MAX_RT\") \\- [RFC7283] (\"Handling Unknown DHCPv6 Messages\") \\- [RFC7550] (\"Issues and Recommendations with Multiple Stateful DHCPv6 Options\") This document provides a unified, corrected, and cleaned-up definition of DHCPv6 that also covers all applicable errata filed against older RFCs (see the list in Appendix A).",
            "Adjusted": "The initial specification of DHCPv6 was defined in RFC3315, and a number of follow-up documents were published over the years: RFC3633 (IPv6 Prefix Options for Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol version 6), RFC3736 (Stateless Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol Service for IPv6), RFC4242 (Information Refresh Time Option for Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol for IPv6), RFC7083 (Modification to Default Values of SOL_MAX_RT and INF_MAX_RT), RFC7283 (Handling Unknown DHCPv6 Messages), and RFC7550 (Issues and Recommendations with Multiple Stateful DHCPv6 Options). This document provides a unified, corrected, and cleaned-up definition of DHCPv6 that also covers all applicable errata filed against older RFCs (see the list in Appendix A)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "As such, it obsoletes the RFCs listed in the previous paragraph.",
            "Adjusted": "As such, this document obsoletes the RFCs listed in the previous paragraph."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Also, there are a small number of mechanisms that were obsoleted; see Section 25 and Appendix A.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

6. Operational Models -> 6.1. Stateless:
{
    "6. Operational Models -> 6.1. Stateless DHCP": [
        {
            "Original": "Stateless DHCP [RFC3736 Service for IPv6\"\")] is used when DHCP is not used for obtaining a lease but a node (DHCP client) desires one or more DHCP \"other configuration\" parameters, such as a list of DNS recursive name servers or DNS domain search lists [RFC3646\"\")].",
            "Adjusted": "Stateless DHCP is used when DHCP is not used for obtaining a lease but a node (DHCP client) desires one or more DHCP \"other configuration\" parameters, such as a list of DNS recursive name servers or DNS domain search lists."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Stateless DHCP may be used when a node initially boots or at any time the software on the node requires some missing or expired configuration information that is available via DHCP.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This is the simplest and most basic operation for DHCP and requires a client (and a server) to support only two messages -- Information-request and Reply.",
            "Adjusted": "Stateless DHCP is the simplest and most basic operation for DHCP and requires a client (and a server) to support only two messages -- Information-request and Reply."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that DHCP servers and relay agents typically also need to support the Relay-forward and Relay-reply messages to accommodate operation when clients and servers are not on the same link.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

