1. Introduction:
{
    "1. Introduction": [
        {
            "Original": "This document describes DHCP for IPv6 (DHCPv6), a client/server protocol that provides managed configuration of devices.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The basic operation of DHCPv6 provides configuration for clients connected to the same link as the server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Relay agent functionality is also defined for enabling communication between clients and servers that are not on the same link.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "DHCPv6 can provide a device with addresses assigned by a DHCPv6 server and other configuration information; this data is carried in options.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "DHCPv6 can be extended through the definition of new options to carry configuration information not specified in this document.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "DHCPv6 also provides a mechanism for automated delegation of IPv6 prefixes using DHCPv6, as originally specified in [RFC3633 version 6\"\")].",
            "Adjusted": "DHCPv6 also provides a mechanism for automated delegation of IPv6 prefixes using DHCPv6, as originally specified in RFC3633."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Through this mechanism, a delegating router can delegate prefixes to requesting routers.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Use of this mechanism is specified as part of [RFC7084] and by [TR-187].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "DHCP can also be used just to provide other configuration options (i.e., no addresses or prefixes).",
            "Adjusted": "DHCPv6 can also be used just to provide other configuration options (i.e., no addresses or prefixes)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "That implies that the server does not have to track any state; thus, this mode is called \"stateless DHCPv6\".",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Mechanisms necessary to support stateless DHCPv6 are much smaller than mechanisms needed to support stateful DHCPv6.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "[RFC3736 Service for IPv6\"\")] was written to document just those portions of DHCPv6 needed to support DHCPv6 stateless operation.",
            "Adjusted": "RFC3736 was written to document just those portions of DHCPv6 needed to support DHCPv6 stateless operation."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The remainder of this introduction summarizes the relationship to the previous DHCPv6 standards (see Section 1.1) and clarifies the stance with regard to DHCPv4 (see Section 1.2).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Section 5 describes the message exchange mechanisms to illustrate DHCP operation rather than provide an exhaustive list of all possible interactions, and Section 6 provides an overview of common operational models.",
            "Adjusted": "Section 5 describes the message exchange mechanisms to illustrate DHCPv6 operation rather than provide an exhaustive list of all possible interactions, and Section 6 provides an overview of common operational models."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Section 18 explains client and server operation in detail.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

