6. Operational Models -> 6.2. DHCP for N:
{
    "6. Operational Models -> 6.2. DHCP for Non-temporary Address Assignment": [
        {
            "Original": "This model of operation was the original motivation for DHCP.",
            "Adjusted": "The DHCP for non-temporary address assignment model of operation was the original motivation for DHCP."
        },
        {
            "Original": "It is appropriate for situations where stateless address autoconfiguration alone is insufficient or impractical, e.g., because of network policy, additional requirements such as dynamic updates to the DNS, or client-specific requirements.",
            "Adjusted": "DHCP for non-temporary address assignment is appropriate for situations where stateless address autoconfiguration alone is insufficient or impractical, e.g., because of network policy, additional requirements such as dynamic updates to the DNS, or client-specific requirements."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The model of operation for non-temporary address assignment is as follows.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server is provided with prefixes from which it may allocate addresses to clients, as well as any related network topology information as to which prefixes are present on which links.",
            "Adjusted": "The server is provided with prefixes from which the server may allocate addresses to clients, as well as any related network topology information as to which prefixes are present on which links."
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client requests a non-temporary address to be assigned by the server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server allocates an address or addresses appropriate for the link on which the client is connected.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server returns the allocated address or addresses to the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Each address has associated preferred and valid lifetimes, which constitute an agreement about the length of time over which the client is allowed to use the address.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client can request an extension of the lifetimes on an address and is required to terminate the use of an address if the valid lifetime of the address expires.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Typically, clients request other configuration parameters, such as the DNS name server addresses and domain search lists, when requesting addresses.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Clients can also request more than one address or set of addresses (see Sections6.6 and 12).",
            "Adjusted": "Clients can also request more than one address or set of addresses (see Sections 6.6 and 12)."
        }
    ]
}

5. Client/Server Exchanges -> 5.1. Clien:
{
    "5. Client/Server Exchanges -> 5.1. Client/Server Exchanges Involving Two Messages": [
        {
            "Original": "When a DHCP client does not need to have a DHCP server assign IP addresses or delegated prefixes to it, the client can obtain other configuration information such as a list of available DNS servers [RFC3646\"\")] or NTP servers [RFC5908 Server Option for DHCPv6\"\")] through a single message and reply exchange with a DHCP server.",
            "Adjusted": "When a DHCP client does not need to have a DHCP server assign IP addresses or delegated prefixes to it, the client can obtain other configuration information such as a list of available DNS servers [RFC3646] or NTP servers [RFC5908 Server Option for DHCPv6] through a single message and reply exchange with a DHCP server."
        },
        {
            "Original": "To obtain other configuration information, the client first sends an Information-request message to the All_DHCP_Relay_Agents_and_Servers multicast address.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Servers respond with a Reply message containing the other configuration information for the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client may also request the server to expedite address assignment and/or prefix delegation by using a two-message exchange instead of the normal four-message exchange as discussed in the next section.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Expedited assignment can be requested by the client, and servers may or may not honor the request (see Sections 18.3.1 and 21.14 for more details and why servers may not honor this request).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Clients may request this expedited service in environments where it is likely that there is only one server available on a link and no expectation that a second server would become available, or when completing the configuration process as quickly as possible is a priority.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "To request the expedited two-message exchange, the client sends a Solicit message to the All_DHCP_Relay_Agents_and_Servers multicast address requesting the assignment of addresses and/or delegated prefixes and other configuration information.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This message includes an indication (the Rapid Commit option; see Section 21.14) that the client is willing to accept an immediate Reply message from the server.",
            "Adjusted": "The Solicit message includes an indication (the Rapid Commit option; see Section 21.14) that the client is willing to accept an immediate Reply message from the server."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server that is willing to commit the assignment of addresses and/or delegated prefixes to the client immediately responds with a Reply message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The configuration information and the addresses and/or delegated prefixes in the Reply message are then immediately available for use by the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Each address or delegated prefix assigned to the client has associated preferred and valid lifetimes specified by the server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "To request an extension of the lifetimes assigned to an address or delegated prefix, the client sends a Renew message to the server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server sends a Reply message to the client with the new lifetimes, allowing the client to continue to use the address or delegated prefix without interruption.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
