6. Operational Models -> 6.6. Multiple A:
{
    "6. Operational Models -> 6.6. Multiple Addresses and Prefixes": [
        {
            "Original": "DHCP allows a client to receive multiple addresses.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "During typical operation, a client sends one instance of an IA_NA option and the server assigns at most one address from each prefix assigned to the link to which the client is attached.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In particular, the server can be configured to serve addresses out of multiple prefixes for a given link.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This is useful in cases such as when a network renumbering event is in progress.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In a typical deployment, the server will grant one address for each IA_NA option (see Section 21.4).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client can explicitly request multiple addresses by sending multiple IA_NA options (and/or IA_TA options; see Section 21.5).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client can send multiple IA_NA (and/or IA_TA) options in its initial transmissions.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Alternatively, it can send an extra Request message with additional new IA_NA (and/or IA_TA) options (or include them in a Renew message).",
            "Adjusted": "Alternatively, the client can send an extra Request message with additional new IA_NA (and/or IA_TA) options (or include them in a Renew message)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The same principle also applies to prefix delegation.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In principle, DHCP allows a client to request new prefixes to be delegated by sending additional IA_PD options (see Section 21.21).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "However, a typical operator usually prefers to delegate a single, larger prefix.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In most deployments, it is recommended that the client request a larger prefix in its initial transmissions rather than request additional prefixes later on.",
            "Adjusted": "In most deployments, it is recommended that the client request a larger prefix in its initial transmissions rather than request additional prefixes later on."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The exact behavior of the server (whether to grant additional addresses and prefixes or not) is up to the server policy and is out of scope for this document.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For more information on how the server distinguishes between IA option instances, see Section 12.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

7. DHCP Constants -> 7.7. Representation:
{
    "7. DHCP Constants -> 7.7. Representation of Time Values and \"Infinity\" as a Time Value": [
        {
            "Original": "All time values for lifetimes, T1, and T2 are unsigned 32-bit integers and are expressed in units of seconds.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The value 0xffffffff is taken to mean \"infinity\" when used as a lifetime (as in [RFC4861\"\"]) or a value for T1 or T2.",
            "Adjusted": "The value 0xffffffff is taken to mean \"infinity\" when used as a lifetime (as in RFC4861) or a value for T1 or T2."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Setting the valid lifetime of an address or a delegated prefix to 0xffffffff (\"infinity\") amounts to a permanent assignment of an address or delegation to a client and should only be used in cases where permanent assignments are desired.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Care should be taken in setting T1 or T2 to 0xffffffff (\"infinity\").",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client will never attempt to extend the lifetimes of any addresses in an IA with T1 set to 0xffffffff.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client will never attempt to use a Rebind message to locate a different server to extend the lifetimes of any addresses in an IA with T2 set to 0xffffffff.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

