11. DHCP Unique Identifier (DUID):
{
    "11. DHCP Unique Identifier (DUID)": [
        {
            "Original": "Each DHCP client and server has a DUID.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "DHCP servers use DUIDs to identify clients for the selection of configuration parameters and in the association of IAs with clients.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "DHCP clients use DUIDs to identify a server in messages where a server needs to be identified.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "See Sections21.2 and 21.3 for details regarding the representation of a DUID in a DHCP message.",
            "Adjusted": "See Sections 21.2 and 21.3 for details regarding the representation of a DUID in a DHCP message."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Clients and servers MUST treat DUIDs as opaque values and MUST only compare DUIDs for equality.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Clients and servers SHOULD NOT in any other way interpret DUIDs.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Clients and servers MUST NOT restrict DUIDs to the types defined in this document, as additional DUID types may be defined in the future.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "It should be noted that an attempt to parse a DUID to obtain a client's link-layer address is unreliable, as there is no guarantee that the client is still using the same link-layer address as when it generated its DUID.",
            "Adjusted": "An attempt to parse a DUID to obtain a client's link-layer address is unreliable, as there is no guarantee that the client is still using the same link-layer address as when the client generated its DUID."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Also, such an attempt will be more and more unreliable as more clients adopt privacy measures such as those defined in [RFC7844].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If this capability is required, it is recommended to rely on the Client Link-Layer Address option instead [RFC6939].",
            "Adjusted": "If the capability to obtain a client's link-layer address is required, it is recommended to rely on the Client Link-Layer Address option instead [RFC6939]."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The DUID is carried in an option because it may be variable in length and because it is not required in all DHCP messages.",
            "Adjusted": "The DUID is carried in an option because the DUID may be variable in length and because the DUID is not required in all DHCP messages."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The DUID is designed to be unique across all DHCP clients and servers, and stable for any specific client or server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "That is, the DUID used by a client or server SHOULD NOT change over time if at all possible; for example, a device's DUID should not change as a result of a change in the device's network hardware or changes to virtual interfaces (e.g., logical PPP (over Ethernet) interfaces that may come and go in Customer Premises Equipment routers).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client may change its DUID as specified in [RFC7844].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The motivation for having more than one type of DUID is that the DUID must be globally unique and must also be easy to generate.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The sort of globally unique identifier that is easy to generate for any given device can differ quite widely.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Also, some devices may not contain any persistent storage.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Retaining a generated DUID in such a device is not possible, so the DUID scheme must accommodate such devices.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

12. Identity Association:
{
    "12. Identity Association": [
        {
            "Original": "An Identity Association (IA) is a construct through which a server and a client can identify, group, and manage a set of related IPv6 addresses or delegated prefixes.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Each IA consists of an IAID and associated configuration information.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The IAID uniquely identifies the IA and MUST be chosen to be unique among the IAIDs for that IA type on the client (e.g., an IA_NA with an IAID of 0 and an IA_PD with an IAID of 0 are each considered unique).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The IAID is chosen by the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For any given use of an IA by the client, the IAID for that IA MUST be consistent across restarts of the DHCP client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client may maintain consistency by either storing the IAID in non-volatile storage or using an algorithm that will consistently produce the same IAID as long as the configuration of the client has not changed.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "There may be no way for a client to maintain consistency of the IAIDs if it does not have non-volatile storage and the client's hardware configuration changes.",
            "Adjusted": "There may be no way for a client to maintain consistency of the IAIDs if the client does not have non-volatile storage and the client's hardware configuration changes."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client uses only one IAID, it can use a well-known value, e.g., zero.",
            "Adjusted": "If the client uses only one IAID, the client can use a well-known value, e.g., zero."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client wishes to obtain a distinctly new address or prefix and deprecate the existing one, the client sends a Release message to the server for the IAs using the original IAID.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client then creates a new IAID, to be used in future messages to obtain leases for the new IA.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

