15. Reliability of Client-Initiated Mess:
{
    "15. Reliability of Client-Initiated Message Exchanges": [
        {
            "Original": "DHCP clients are responsible for reliable delivery of messages in the client-initiated message exchanges described inSection 18.",
            "Adjusted": "DHCP clients are responsible for reliable delivery of messages in the client-initiated message exchanges described in Section 18."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If a DHCP client fails to receive an expected response from a server, the client must retransmit its message according to the retransmission strategy described in this section.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that the procedure described in this section is slightly modified when used with the Solicit message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The modified procedure is described in Section 18.2.1.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client begins the message exchange by transmitting a message to the server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The message exchange terminates when either (1) the client successfully receives the appropriate response or responses from a server or servers or (2) the message exchange is considered to have failed according to the retransmission mechanism described below.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client MUST update an \"elapsed-time\" value within an Elapsed Time option (see Section 21.9) in the retransmitted message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In some cases, the client may also need to modify values in IA Address options (see Section 21.6) or IA Prefix options (see Section 21.22) if a valid lifetime for any of the client's leases expires before retransmission.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Thus, whenever this document refers to a \"retransmission\" of a client's message, it refers to both modifying the original message and sending this new message instance to the server.",
            "Adjusted": "Thus, whenever this document refers to a \"retransmission\" of a client's message, the retransmission refers to both modifying the original message and sending this new message instance to the server."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client retransmission behavior is controlled and described by the following variables: RT Retransmission timeout IRT Initial retransmission time MRC Maximum retransmission count MRT Maximum retransmission time MRD Maximum retransmission duration RAND Randomization factor Specific values for each of these parameters relevant to the various messages are given in the subsections of Section 18.2, using values defined in Table 1 in Section 7.6.",
            "Adjusted": "The client retransmission behavior is controlled and described by the following variables: RT (Retransmission timeout), IRT (Initial retransmission time), MRC (Maximum retransmission count), MRT (Maximum retransmission time), MRD (Maximum retransmission duration), and RAND (Randomization factor). Specific values for each of these parameters relevant to the various messages are given in the subsections of Section 18.2, using values defined in Table 1 in Section 7.6."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The algorithm for RAND is common across all message transmissions.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "With each message transmission or retransmission, the client sets RT according to the rules given below.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If RT expires before the message exchange terminates, the client recomputes RT and retransmits the message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Each of the computations of a new RT includes a randomization factor (RAND), which is a random number chosen with a uniform distribution between -0.1 and +0.1.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The randomization factor is included to minimize synchronization of messages transmitted by DHCP clients.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The algorithm for choosing a random number does not need to be cryptographically sound.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The algorithm SHOULD produce a different sequence of random numbers from each invocation of the DHCP client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "RT for the first message transmission is based on IRT: RT = IRT + RAND*IRT RT for each subsequent message transmission is based on the previous value of RT: RT = 2*RTprev + RAND*RTprev MRT specifies an upper bound on the value of RT (disregarding the randomization added by the use of RAND).",
            "Adjusted": "RT for the first message transmission is based on IRT: RT = IRT + RAND*IRT. RT for each subsequent message transmission is based on the previous value of RT: RT = 2*RTprev + RAND*RTprev. MRT specifies an upper bound on the value of RT (disregarding the randomization added by the use of RAND)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If MRT has a value of 0, there is no upper limit on the value of RT.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Otherwise: if (RT > MRT) RT = MRT + RAND*MRT MRC specifies an upper bound on the number of times a client may retransmit a message.",
            "Adjusted": "Otherwise: if (RT > MRT) then RT = MRT + RAND*MRT. MRC specifies an upper bound on the number of times a client may retransmit a message."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Unless MRC is zero, the message exchange fails once the client has transmitted the message MRC times.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "MRD specifies an upper bound on the length of time a client may retransmit a message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Unless MRD is zero, the message exchange fails once MRD seconds have elapsed since the client first transmitted the message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If both MRC and MRD are non-zero, the message exchange fails whenever either of the conditions specified in the previous two paragraphs is met.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If both MRC and MRD are zero, the client continues to transmit the message until it receives a response.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client is not expected to listen for a response during the entire RT period and may turn off listening capabilities after waiting at least the shorter of RT and MAX_WAIT_TIME due to power consumption saving or other reasons.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Of course, a client MUST listen for a Reconfigure if it has negotiated for its use with the server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

