{
    "18.2. Client Behavior": [
        {
            "Original": "A client uses the Solicit message to discover DHCP servers configured to assign leases or return other configuration parameters on the link to which the client is attached.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client uses Request, Renew, Rebind, Release, and Decline messages during the normal lifecycle of addresses and delegated prefixes.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "When a client detects that it may have moved to a new link, it uses Confirm if it only has addresses and Rebind if it has delegated prefixes (and addresses).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "It uses Information-request messages when it needs configuration information but no addresses and no prefixes.",
            "Adjusted": "The client uses Information-request messages when it needs configuration information but no addresses and no prefixes."
        },
        {
            "Original": "When a client requests multiple IA option types or multiple instances of the same IA types in a Solicit, Request, Renew, or Rebind, it is possible that the available server(s) may only be configured to offer a subset of them.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "When possible, the client SHOULD use the best configuration available and continue to request the additional IAs in subsequent messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This allows the client to maintain a single session and state machine.",
            "Adjusted": "Using the best configuration available and continuing to request additional IAs allows the client to maintain a single session and state machine."
        },
        {
            "Original": "In practice, especially in the case of handling IA_NA and IA_PD requests [RFC7084], this situation should be rare or a result of a temporary operational error.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Thus, it is more likely that the client will get all configuration if it continues, in each subsequent configuration exchange, to request all the configuration information it is programmed to try to obtain, including any stateful configuration options for which no results were returned in previous message exchanges.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Upon receipt of a Reconfigure message from the server, a client responds with a Renew, Rebind, or Information-request message as indicated by the Reconfigure Message option (see Section 21.19).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client SHOULD be suspicious of the Reconfigure message (they may be faked), and it MUST NOT abandon any resources it might have already obtained.",
            "Adjusted": "The client SHOULD be suspicious of the Reconfigure message (Reconfigure messages may be faked), and the client MUST NOT abandon any resources it might have already obtained."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client SHOULD treat the Reconfigure message as if the T1 timer had expired.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client will expect the server to send IAs and/or other configuration information to the client in a Reply message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client has a source address of sufficient scope that can be used by the server as a return address and the client has received a Server Unicast option (see Section 21.12) from the server, the client SHOULD unicast any Request, Renew, Release, and Decline messages to the server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Use of unicast may avoid delays due to the relaying of messages by relay agents, as well as avoid overhead on servers due to the delivery of client messages to multiple servers.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "However, requiring the client to relay all DHCP messages through a relay agent enables the inclusion of relay agent options in all messages sent by the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server should enable the use of unicast only when relay agent options will not be used.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

