18. DHCP Configuration Exchanges -> 18.3:
{
    "18. DHCP Configuration Exchanges -> 18.3. Server Behavior -> 18.3.1. Receipt of Solicit Messages": [
        {
            "Original": "SeeSection 18.4 for details regarding the handling of Solicit messages received via unicast.",
            "Adjusted": "See Section 18.4 for details regarding the handling of Solicit messages received via unicast."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Unicast transmission of Solicit messages is not allowed, regardless of whether the Server Unicast option (see Section 21.12) is configured or not.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server determines the information about the client and its location as described in Section 13 and checks its administrative policy about responding to the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server is not permitted to respond to the client, the server discards the Solicit message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For example, if the administrative policy for the server is that it may only respond to a client that is willing to accept a Reconfigure message, if the client does not include a Reconfigure Accept option (see Section 21.20) in the Solicit message, the server discards the Solicit message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If (1) the server is permitted to respond to the client, (2) the client has not included a Rapid Commit option (see Section 21.14) in the Solicit message, or (3) the server has not been configured to respond with committed assignments of leases and other resources, the server sends an Advertise message to the client as described in Section 18.3.9.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client has included a Rapid Commit option in the Solicit message and the server has been configured to respond with committed assignments of leases and other resources, the server responds to the Solicit with a Reply message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server produces the Reply message as though it had received a Request message as described in Section 18.3.2.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server transmits the Reply message as described in Section 18.3.10.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MUST commit the assignment of any addresses and delegated prefixes or other configuration information before sending a Reply message to a client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In this case, the server includes a Rapid Commit option in the Reply message to indicate that the Reply is in response to a Solicit message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "DISCUSSION: When using the Solicit/Reply message exchange, the server commits the assignment of any leases before sending the Reply message.",
            "Adjusted": "When using the Solicit/Reply message exchange, the server commits the assignment of any leases before sending the Reply message."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client can assume that it has been assigned the leases in the Reply message and does not need to send a Request message for those leases.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Typically, servers that are configured to use the Solicit/Reply message exchange will be deployed so that only one server will respond to a Solicit message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If more than one server responds, the client will only use the leases from one of the servers, while the leases from the other servers will be committed to the client but not used by the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

18. DHCP Configuration Exchanges:
{
    "18. DHCP Configuration Exchanges": [
        {
            "Original": "A client initiates a message exchange with a server or servers to acquire or update configuration information of interest.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client has many reasons to initiate the configuration exchange.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Some of the more common ones are: 1\\.",
            "Adjusted": "Some of the more common reasons are:"
        },
        {
            "Original": "as part of the operating system configuration/bootstrap process, 2\\.",
            "Adjusted": "As part of the operating system configuration/bootstrap process,"
        },
        {
            "Original": "when requested to do so by the application layer (through an operating-system-specific API), 3\\.",
            "Adjusted": "When requested to do so by the application layer (through an operating-system-specific API),"
        },
        {
            "Original": "when a Router Advertisement indicates that DHCPv6 is available for address configuration (see[Section 4.2 of [RFC4861]](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc4861#section-4.2)), 4\\.",
            "Adjusted": "When a Router Advertisement indicates that DHCPv6 is available for address configuration (see Section 4.2 of RFC4861),"
        },
        {
            "Original": "as required to extend the lifetime of address(es) and/or delegated prefix(es), using Renew and Rebind messages, or 5\\.",
            "Adjusted": "As required to extend the lifetime of address(es) and/or delegated prefix(es), using Renew and Rebind messages, or"
        },
        {
            "Original": "upon the receipt of a Reconfigure message, when requested to do so by a server.",
            "Adjusted": "Upon the receipt of a Reconfigure message, when requested to do so by a server."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client is responsible for creating IAs and requesting that a server assign addresses and/or delegated prefixes to the IAs.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client first creates the IAs and assigns IAIDs to them.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client then transmits a Solicit message containing the IA options describing the IAs.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client MUST NOT be using any of the addresses or delegated prefixes for which it tries to obtain the bindings by sending the Solicit message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In particular, if the client had some valid bindings and has chosen to start the server discovery process to obtain the same bindings from a different server, the client MUST stop using the addresses and delegated prefixes for the bindings that it had obtained from the previous server (see Section 18.2.7 for more details on what \"stop using\" means in this context) and that it is now trying to obtain from a new server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A DHCP client that does not need to have a DHCP server assign IP addresses or delegated prefixes to it can obtain configuration information such as a list of available DNS servers [RFC3646\"\")] or NTP servers [RFC5908 Server Option for DHCPv6\"\")] through a single message and reply exchange with a DHCP server.",
            "Adjusted": "A DHCP client that does not need to have a DHCP server assign IP addresses or delegated prefixes to it can obtain configuration information such as a list of available DNS servers (RFC3646) or NTP servers (RFC5908 Server Option for DHCPv6) through a single message and reply exchange with a DHCP server."
        },
        {
            "Original": "To obtain configuration information, the client first sends an Information-request message (see Section 18.2.6) to the All_DHCP_Relay_Agents_and_Servers multicast address.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Servers respond with a Reply message containing the configuration information for the client (see Section 18.3.6).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "To request the assignment of one or more addresses or delegated prefixes, a client first locates a DHCP server and then requests the assignment of addresses/prefixes and other configuration information from the server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client does this by sending the Solicit message (see Section 18.2.1) to the All_DHCP_Relay_Agents_and_Servers multicast address and collecting Advertise messages from the servers that respond to the client's message; the client then selects a server from which it wants to obtain configuration information.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This process is referred to as server discovery.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "When the client has selected the server, it sends a Request message to that server as described in Section 18.2.2.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client willing to perform the Solicit/Reply message exchange described in Section 18.2.1 includes a Rapid Commit option (see Section 21.14) in its Solicit message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Servers that can assign addresses or delegated prefixes to the IAs respond to the client with an Advertise message or Reply message if the client included a Rapid Commit option and the server is configured to accept it.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server responds with an Advertise message, the client initiates a configuration exchange as described in Section 18.2.2.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A server may initiate a message exchange with a client by sending a Reconfigure message to cause the client to send a Renew, Rebind, or Information-request message to refresh its configuration information as soon as the Reconfigure message is received by the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Figure 9 shows a timeline diagram of the messages exchanged between a client and two servers for the typical lifecycle of one or more leases.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This starts with the four-message Solicit/Advertise/ Request/Reply exchange to obtain the lease(s), followed by a two-message Renew/Reply exchange to extend the lifetime on the lease(s), and then ends with a two-message Release/Reply exchange to end the client's use of the lease(s).",
