18. DHCP Configuration Exchanges -> 18.3:
{
    "18.3. Server Behavior": [
        {
            "Original": "For this discussion, the server is assumed to have been configured in an implementation-specific manner with configurations of interest to clients.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A server sends an Advertise message in response to each valid Solicit message it receives to announce the availability of the server to the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In most cases, the server will send a Reply in response to Request, Confirm, Renew, Rebind, Decline, Release, and Information-request messages sent by a client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server will also send a Reply in response to a Solicit with a Rapid Commit option (seeSection 21.14) when the server is configured to respond with committed lease assignments.",
            "Adjusted": "The server will also send a Reply in response to a Solicit with a Rapid Commit option (see Section 21.14) when the server is configured to respond with committed lease assignments."
        },
        {
            "Original": "These Advertise and Reply messages MUST always contain the Server Identifier option (see Section 21.3) containing the server's DUID and the Client Identifier option (see Section 21.2) from the client message if one was present.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In most response messages, the server includes options containing configuration information for the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server must be aware of the recommendations on packet sizes and the use of fragmentation as discussed in [Section 5 of [RFC8200]](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8200#section-5).",
            "Adjusted": "The server must be aware of the recommendations on packet sizes and the use of fragmentation as discussed in Section 5 of RFC8200."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client included an Option Request option (see Section 21.7) in its message, the server includes options in the response message containing configuration parameters for all of the options identified in the Option Request option that the server has been configured to return to the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MAY return additional options to the client if it has been configured to do so.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Any message sent from a client may arrive at the server encapsulated in one or more Relay-forward messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MUST use the received message to construct the proper Relay-reply message to allow the response to the received message to be relayed through the same relay agents (in reverse order) as the original client message; see Section 19.3 for more details.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server may also need to record this information with each client in case it is needed to send a Reconfigure message at a later time, unless the server has been configured with addresses that can be used to send Reconfigure messages directly to the client (see Section 18.3.11).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that servers that support leasequery [RFC5007] also need to record this information.",
            "Adjusted": "Note that servers that support leasequery (RFC5007) also need to record this information."
        },
        {
            "Original": "By sending Reconfigure messages, the server MAY initiate a configuration exchange to cause DHCP clients to obtain new addresses, prefixes, and other configuration information.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For example, an administrator may use a server-initiated configuration exchange when links in the DHCP domain are to be renumbered or when other configuration options are updated, perhaps because servers are moved, added, or removed.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "When a client receives a Reconfigure message from the server, the client initiates sending a Renew, Rebind, or Information-request message as indicated by msg-type in the Reconfigure Message option (see Section 21.19).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server sends IAs and/or other configuration information to the client in a Reply message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MAY include options containing the IAs and new values for other configuration parameters in the Reply message, even if those IAs and parameters were not requested in the client's message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

18. DHCP Configuration Exchanges -> 18.2:
{
    "18. DHCP Configuration Exchanges -> 18.2. Client Behavior -> 18.2.1. Creation and Transmission of Solicit Messages": [
        {
            "Original": "The client sets the \"msg-type\" field to SOLICIT.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client generates a transaction ID and inserts this value in the \"transaction-id\" field.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client MUST include a Client Identifier option (seeSection 21.2) to identify itself to the server.",
            "Adjusted": "The client MUST include a Client Identifier option (see Section 21.2) to identify itself to the server."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client includes IA options for any IAs to which it wants the server to assign leases.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client MUST include an Elapsed Time option (see Section 21.9) to indicate how long the client has been trying to complete the current DHCP message exchange.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client uses IA_NA options (see Section 21.4) to request the assignment of non-temporary addresses, IA_TA options (see Section 21.5) to request the assignment of temporary addresses, and IA_PD options (see Section 21.21) to request prefix delegation.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "IA_NA, IA_TA, or IA_PD options, or a combination of all, can be included in DHCP messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In addition, multiple instances of any IA option type can be included.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client MAY include addresses in IA Address options (see Section 21.6) encapsulated within IA_NA and IA_TA options as hints to the server about the addresses for which the client has a preference.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client MAY include values in IA Prefix options (see Section 21.22) encapsulated within IA_PD options as hints for the delegated prefix and/or prefix length for which the client has a preference.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "See Section 18.2.4 for more on prefix-length hints.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client MUST include an Option Request option (ORO) (see Section 21.7) to request the SOL_MAX_RT option (see Section 21.24) and any other options the client is interested in receiving.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client MAY additionally include instances of those options that are identified in the Option Request option, with data values as hints to the server about parameter values the client would like to have returned.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client includes a Reconfigure Accept option (see Section 21.20) if the client is willing to accept Reconfigure messages from the server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client MUST NOT include any other options in the Solicit message, except as specifically allowed in the definition of individual options.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The first Solicit message from the client on the interface SHOULD be delayed by a random amount of time between 0 and SOL_MAX_DELAY.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This random delay helps desynchronize clients that start a DHCP session at the same time, such as after recovery from a power failure or after a router outage after seeing that DHCP is available in Router Advertisement messages (see [Section 4.2 of [RFC4861]](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc4861#section-4.2)).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client transmits the message according to Section 15, using the following parameters: IRT SOL_TIMEOUT MRT SOL_MAX_RT MRC 0 MRD 0 A client that wishes to use the Rapid Commit two-message exchange includes a Rapid Commit option (see Section 21.14) in its Solicit message.",
            "Adjusted": "The client transmits the message according to Section 15, using the following parameters: IRT SOL_TIMEOUT, MRT SOL_MAX_RT, MRC 0, MRD 0. A client that wishes to use the Rapid Commit two-message exchange includes a Rapid Commit option (see Section 21.14) in its Solicit message."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client may receive a number of different replies from different servers.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client will make note of any valid Advertise messages that it receives.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client will discard any Reply messages that do not contain the Rapid Commit option.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Upon receipt of a valid Reply with the Rapid Commit option, the client processes the message as described in Section 18.2.10.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "At the end of the first RT period, if no suitable Reply messages are received but the client has valid Advertise messages, then the client processes the Advertise as described in Section 18.2.9.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client subsequently receives a valid Reply message that includes a Rapid Commit option, it does one of the following: \\- processes the Reply message as described in Section 18.2.10 and discards any Reply messages received in response to the Request message \\- processes any Reply messages received in response to the Request message and discards the Reply message that includes the Rapid Commit option If the client is waiting for an Advertise message, the mechanism described in Section 15 is modified as follows for use in the transmission of Solicit messages.",
            "Adjusted": "If the client subsequently receives a valid Reply message that includes a Rapid Commit option, it does one of the following: processes the Reply message as described in Section 18.2.10 and discards any Reply messages received in response to the Request message, or processes any Reply messages received in response to the Request message and discards the Reply message that includes the Rapid Commit option. If the client is waiting for an Advertise message, the mechanism described in Section 15 is modified as follows for use in the transmission of Solicit messages."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The message exchange is not terminated by the receipt of an Advertise before the first RT has elapsed.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Rather, the client collects valid Advertise messages until the first RT has elapsed.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Also, the first RT MUST be selected to be strictly greater than IRT by choosing RAND to be strictly greater than 0.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client MUST collect valid Advertise messages for the first RT seconds, unless it receives a valid Advertise message with a preference value of 255.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The preference value is carried in the Preference option (see Section 21.8).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Any valid Advertise that does not include a Preference option is considered to have a preference value of 0.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client receives a valid Advertise message that includes a Preference option with a preference value of 255, the client immediately begins a client-initiated message exchange (as described in Section 18.2.2) by sending a Request message to the server from which the Advertise message was received.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client receives a valid Advertise message that does not include a Preference option with a preference value of 255, the client continues to wait until the first RT elapses.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the first RT elapses and the client has received a valid Advertise message, the client SHOULD continue with a client-initiated message exchange by sending a Request message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client does not receive any valid Advertise messages before the first RT has elapsed, it then applies the retransmission mechanism described in Section 15.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client terminates the retransmission process as soon as it receives any valid Advertise message, and the client acts on the received Advertise message without waiting for any additional Advertise messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A DHCP client SHOULD choose MRC and MRD values of 0.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the DHCP client is configured with either MRC or MRD set to a value other than 0, it MUST stop trying to configure the interface if the message exchange fails.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "After the DHCP client stops trying to configure the interface, it SHOULD restart the reconfiguration process after some external event, such as user input, system restart, or when the client is attached to a new link.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

18. DHCP Configuration Exchanges -> 18.3:
{
    "18. DHCP Configuration Exchanges -> 18.3. Server Behavior -> 18.3.6. Receipt of Information-request Messages": [
        {
            "Original": "SeeSection 18.4 for details regarding the handling of Information-request messages received via unicast.",
            "Adjusted": "See Section 18.4 for details regarding the handling of Information-request messages received via unicast."
        },
        {
            "Original": "When the server receives an Information-request message, the client is requesting configuration information that does not include the assignment of any leases.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server determines all configuration parameters appropriate to the client, based on the server configuration policies known to the server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server constructs a Reply message by setting the \"msg-type\" field to REPLY and copying the transaction ID from the Information-request message into the \"transaction-id\" field.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MUST include a Server Identifier option (see Section 21.3) containing the server's DUID in the Reply message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client included a Client Identifier option (see Section 21.2) in the Information-request message, the server copies that option to the Reply message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server includes options containing configuration information to be returned to the client as described in Section 18.3.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MAY include additional options that were not requested by the client in the Information-request message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the Information-request message received from the client did not include a Client Identifier option, the server SHOULD respond with a Reply message containing any configuration parameters that are not determined by the client's identity.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server chooses not to respond, the client may continue to retransmit the Information-request message indefinitely.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "18. DHCP Configuration Exchanges -> 18.3. Server Behavior -> 18.3.10. Transmission of Advertise and Reply Messages": [
        {
            "Original": "If the original message was received directly by the server, the server unicasts the Advertise or Reply message directly to the client using the address in the source address field from the IP datagram in which the original message was received.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Advertise or Reply message MUST be unicast through the interface on which the original message was received.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the original message was received in a Relay-forward message, the server constructs a Relay-reply message with the Reply message in the payload of a Relay Message option (seeSection 21.10).",
            "Adjusted": "If the original message was received in a Relay-forward message, the server constructs a Relay-reply message with the Reply message in the payload of a Relay Message option (see Section 21.10)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the Relay-forward messages included an Interface-Id option (see Section 21.18), the server copies that option to the Relay-reply message.",
