        {
            "Original": "The server includes its server identifier in a Server Identifier option (seeSection 21.3) and copies the Client Identifier option (see Section 21.2) from the Solicit message into the Advertise message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MAY add a Preference option (see Section 21.8) to carry the preference value for the Advertise message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server implementation SHOULD allow the setting of a server preference value by the administrator.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server preference value MUST default to 0 unless otherwise configured by the server administrator.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server includes a Reconfigure Accept option (see Section 21.20) if the server wants to indicate that it supports the Reconfigure mechanism.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This information may be used by the client during the server selection process.",
            "Adjusted": "The Reconfigure Accept option information may be used by the client during the server selection process."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server includes the options the server will return to the client in a subsequent Reply message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The information in these options may be used by the client in the selection of a server if the client receives more than one Advertise message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MUST include options in the Advertise message containing configuration parameters for all of the options identified in the Option Request option (see Section 21.7) in the Solicit message that the server has been configured to return to the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the Option Request option includes a container option, the server MUST include all the options that are eligible to be encapsulated in the container.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Option Request option MAY be used to signal support for a feature even when that option is encapsulated, as in the case of the Prefix Exclude option [RFC6603].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In this case, special processing is required by the server.",
            "Adjusted": "When the Option Request option is used to signal support for a feature with encapsulated options, special processing is required by the server."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MAY return additional options to the client if it has been configured to do so.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MUST include IA options in the Advertise message containing any addresses and/or delegated prefixes that would be assigned to IAs contained in the Solicit message from the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client has included addresses in the IA Address options (see Section 21.6) in the Solicit message, the server MAY use those addresses as hints about the addresses that the client would like to receive.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client has included IA Prefix options (see Section 21.22), the server MAY use the prefix contained in the \"IPv6-prefix\" field and/or the prefix length contained in the \"prefix-length\" field as hints about the prefixes the client would like to receive.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server is not going to assign an address or delegated prefix received as a hint in the Solicit message, the server MUST NOT include this address or delegated prefix in the Advertise message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server will not assign any addresses to an IA_NA or IA_TA in subsequent Request messages from the client, the server MUST include the IA option in the Advertise message with no addresses in that IA and a Status Code option (see Section 21.13) encapsulated in the IA option containing status code NoAddrsAvail.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server will not assign any prefixes to an IA_PD in subsequent Request messages from the client, the server MUST include the IA_PD option (see Section 21.21) in the Advertise message with no prefixes in the IA_PD option and a Status Code option encapsulated in the IA_PD containing status code NoPrefixAvail.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Transmission of Advertise messages is described in the next section.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "18. DHCP Configuration Exchanges -> 18.3. Server Behavior -> 18.3.4. Receipt of Renew Messages": [
        {
            "Original": "SeeSection 18.4 for details regarding the handling of Renew messages received via unicast.",
            "Adjusted": "See Section 18.4 for details regarding the handling of Renew messages received via unicast."
        },
        {
            "Original": "For each IA in the Renew message from a client, the server locates the client's binding and verifies that the information in the IA from the client matches the information stored for that client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server finds the client entry for the IA, the server sends the IA back to the client with new lifetimes and, if applicable, T1/T2 times.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server is unable to extend the lifetimes of an address or delegated prefix in the IA, the server MAY choose not to include the IA Address option (see Section 21.6) for that address or IA Prefix option (see Section 21.22) for that delegated prefix.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server chooses to include the IA Address or IA Prefix option for such an address or delegated prefix, the server SHOULD set T1 and T2 values to the valid lifetime for the IA option unless the server also includes other addresses or delegated prefixes that the server is able to extend for the IA.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Setting T1 and T2 to values equal to the valid lifetime informs the client that the leases associated with said IA will not be extended, so there is no point in trying.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Also, it avoids generating unnecessary traffic as the remaining lifetime approaches 0.",
            "Adjusted": "Also, setting T1 and T2 to values equal to the valid lifetime avoids generating unnecessary traffic as the remaining lifetime approaches 0."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server may choose to change the list of addresses or delegated prefixes and the lifetimes in IAs that are returned to the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server finds that any of the addresses in the IA are not appropriate for the link to which the client is attached, the server returns the address to the client with lifetimes of 0.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server finds that any of the delegated prefixes in the IA are not appropriate for the link to which the client is attached, the server returns the delegated prefix to the client with lifetimes of 0.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For each IA for which the server cannot find a client entry, the server has the following choices, depending on the server's policy and configuration information: \\- If the server is configured to create new bindings as a result of processing Renew messages, the server SHOULD create a binding and return the IA with assigned addresses or delegated prefixes with lifetimes and, if applicable, T1/T2 times and other information requested by the client.",
            "Adjusted": "For each IA for which the server cannot find a client entry, the server has the following choices, depending on the server's policy and configuration information: If the server is configured to create new bindings as a result of processing Renew messages, the server SHOULD create a binding and return the IA with assigned addresses or delegated prefixes with lifetimes and, if applicable, T1/T2 times and other information requested by the client."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client included the IA Prefix option within the IA_PD option (see Section 21.21) with a zero value in the \"IPv6-prefix\" field and a non-zero value in the \"prefix-length\" field, the server MAY use the \"prefix-length\" value as a hint for the length of the prefixes to be assigned (see [RFC8168] for further details on prefix-length hints).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- If the server is configured to create new bindings as a result of processing Renew messages but the server will not assign any leases to an IA, the server returns the IA option containing a Status Code option (see Section 21.13) with the NoAddrsAvail or NoPrefixAvail status code and a status message for a user.",
            "Adjusted": "If the server is configured to create new bindings as a result of processing Renew messages but the server will not assign any leases to an IA, the server returns the IA option containing a Status Code option (see Section 21.13) with the NoAddrsAvail or NoPrefixAvail status code and a status message for a user."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- If the server does not support creation of new bindings for the client sending a Renew message or if this behavior is disabled according to the server's policy or configuration information, the server returns the IA option containing a Status Code option with the NoBinding status code and a status message for a user.",
            "Adjusted": "If the server does not support creation of new bindings for the client sending a Renew message or if this behavior is disabled according to the server's policy or configuration information, the server returns the IA option containing a Status Code option with the NoBinding status code and a status message for a user."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server constructs a Reply message by setting the \"msg-type\" field to REPLY and copying the transaction ID from the Renew message into the \"transaction-id\" field.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MUST include in the Reply message a Server Identifier option (see Section 21.3) containing the server's DUID and the Client Identifier option (see Section 21.2) from the Renew message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server includes other options containing configuration information to be returned to the client as described in Section 18.3.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MAY include options containing the IAs and values for other configuration parameters, even if those parameters were not requested in the Renew message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The T1/T2 values set in each applicable IA option for a Reply MUST be the same across all IAs.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MUST determine the T1/T2 values across all of the applicable client's bindings in the Reply.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This facilitates the client being able to renew all of the bindings at the same time.",
            "Adjusted": "Setting the same T1/T2 values across all IAs facilitates the client being able to renew all of the bindings at the same time."
        }
    ]
}

20. Authentication of DHCP Messages -> 2:
{
    "20. Authentication of DHCP Messages -> 20.2. Summary of DHCP Authentication": [
        {
            "Original": "Authentication of DHCP messages is accomplished through the use of the Authentication option (seeSection 21.11).",
            "Adjusted": "Authentication of DHCP messages is accomplished through the use of the Authentication option (see Section 21.11)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The authentication information carried in the Authentication option can be used to reliably identify the source of a DHCP message and to confirm that the contents of the DHCP message have not been tampered with.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Authentication option provides a framework for multiple authentication protocols.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "One such protocol, RKAP, is defined in Section 20.4.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Other protocols defined in the future will be specified in separate documents.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Any DHCP message MUST NOT include more than one Authentication option.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The protocol field in the Authentication option identifies the specific protocol used to generate the authentication information carried in the option.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The algorithm field identifies a specific algorithm within the authentication protocol; for example, the algorithm field specifies the hash algorithm used to generate the Message Authentication Code (MAC) in the Authentication option.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The RDM field specifies the type of replay detection used in the replay detection field.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

18. DHCP Configuration Exchanges -> 18.2:
{
    "18. DHCP Configuration Exchanges -> 18.2. Client Behavior -> 18.2.10. Receipt of Reply Messages": [
        {
            "Original": "If the client receives a NotOnLink status from the server in response to a Solicit (with a Rapid Commit option; seeSection 21.14) or a Request, the client can either reissue the message without specifying any addresses or restart the DHCP server discovery process (see Section 18).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the Reply was received in response to a Solicit (with a Rapid Commit option), Request, Renew, or Rebind message, the client updates the information it has recorded about IAs from the IA options contained in the Reply message: \\- Calculate T1 and T2 times (based on T1 and T2 values sent in the packet and the packet reception time), if appropriate for the IA type.",
            "Adjusted": "If the Reply message was received in response to a Solicit (with a Rapid Commit option), Request, Renew, or Rebind message, the client updates the information it has recorded about Identity Associations (IAs) from the IA options contained in the Reply message: - Calculate T1 and T2 times (based on T1 and T2 values sent in the packet and the packet reception time), if appropriate for the IA type."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- Add any new leases in the IA option to the IA as recorded by the client.",
            "Adjusted": "- Add any new leases in the IA option to the Identity Association as recorded by the client."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- Update lifetimes for any leases in the IA option that the client already has recorded in the IA.",
            "Adjusted": "- Update lifetimes for any leases in the IA option that the client already has recorded in the Identity Association."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- Discard any leases from the IA, as recorded by the client, that have a valid lifetime of 0 in the IA Address or IA Prefix option.",
            "Adjusted": "- Discard any leases from the Identity Association, as recorded by the client, that have a valid lifetime of 0 in the IA Address or IA Prefix option."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- Leave unchanged any information about leases the client has recorded in the IA but that were not included in the IA from the server.",
            "Adjusted": "- Leave unchanged any information about leases the client has recorded in the Identity Association but that were not included in the IA from the server."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client can operate with the addresses and/or prefixes obtained from the server: \\- The client uses the addresses, delegated prefixes, and other information from any IAs that do not contain a Status Code option with the NoAddrsAvail or NoPrefixAvail status code.",
            "Adjusted": "If the client can operate with the addresses and/or prefixes obtained from the server: - The client uses the addresses, delegated prefixes, and other information from any Identity Associations that do not contain a Status Code option with the NoAddrsAvail or NoPrefixAvail status code."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client MAY include the IAs for which it received the NoAddrsAvail or NoPrefixAvail status code, with no addresses or prefixes, in subsequent Renew and Rebind messages sent to the server, to retry obtaining the addresses or prefixes for these IAs.",
            "Adjusted": "The client MAY include the Identity Associations for which it received the NoAddrsAvail or NoPrefixAvail status code, with no addresses or prefixes, in subsequent Renew and Rebind messages sent to the server, to retry obtaining the addresses or prefixes for these IAs."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- The client MUST perform duplicate address detection as per [Section 5.4 of [RFC4862]](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc4862#section-5.4), which does list some exceptions, on each of the received addresses in any IAs on which it has not performed duplicate address detection during processing of any of the previous Reply messages from the server.",
            "Adjusted": "- The client MUST perform duplicate address detection as per Section 5.4 of RFC4862, which does list some exceptions, on each of the received addresses in any Identity Associations on which it has not performed duplicate address detection during processing of any of the previous Reply messages from the server."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client performs the duplicate address detection before using the received addresses for any traffic.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If any of the addresses are found to be in use on the link, the client sends a Decline message to the server for those addresses as described in Section 18.2.8.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- For each assigned address that does not have any associated reachability information (see the definition of \"on-link\" in [Section 2.1 of [RFC4861]](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc4861#section-2.1)), in order to avoid the problems described in [RFC4943], the client MUST NOT assume that any addresses are reachable on-link as a result of receiving an IA_NA or IA_TA.",
            "Adjusted": "- For each assigned address that does not have any associated reachability information (see the definition of \"on-link\" in Section 2.1 of RFC4861), in order to avoid the problems described in RFC4943, the client MUST NOT assume that any addresses are reachable on-link as a result of receiving an IA_NA or IA_TA."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Addresses obtained from an IA_NA or IA_TA MUST NOT be used to form an implicit prefix with a length other than 128.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- For each delegated prefix, the client assigns a subnet to each of the links to which the associated interfaces are attached.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "When a client subnets a delegated prefix, it must assign additional bits to the prefix to generate unique, longer prefixes.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For example, if the client in Figure 1 were delegated 2001:db8:0::/48, it might generate 2001:db8:0:1::/64 and 2001:db8:0:2::/64 for assignment to the two links in the subscriber network.",
            "Adjusted": "For example, if the client were delegated 2001:db8:0::/48, it might generate 2001:db8:0:1::/64 and 2001:db8:0:2::/64 for assignment to the two links in the subscriber network."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client were delegated 2001:db8:0::/48 and 2001:db8:5::/48, it might assign 2001:db8:0:1::/64 and 2001:db8:5:1::/64 to one of the links, and 2001:db8:0:2::/64 and 2001:db8:5:2::/64 for assignment to the other link.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the client uses a delegated prefix to configure addresses on interfaces on itself or other nodes behind it, the preferred and valid lifetimes of those addresses MUST be no longer than the remaining preferred and valid lifetimes, respectively, for the delegated prefix at any time.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In particular, if the delegated prefix or a prefix derived from it is advertised for stateless address autoconfiguration [RFC4862], the advertised preferred and valid lifetimes MUST NOT exceed the corresponding remaining lifetimes of the delegated prefix.",
            "Adjusted": "In particular, if the delegated prefix or a prefix derived from it is advertised for stateless address autoconfiguration RFC4862, the advertised preferred and valid lifetimes MUST NOT exceed the corresponding remaining lifetimes of the delegated prefix."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Management of the specific configuration information is detailed in the definition of each option in Section 21.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the Reply message contains any IAs but the client finds no usable addresses and/or delegated prefixes in any of these IAs, the client may either try another server (perhaps restarting the DHCP server discovery process) or use the Information-request message to obtain other configuration information only.",
            "Adjusted": "If the Reply message contains any Identity Associations but the client finds no usable addresses and/or delegated prefixes in any of these IAs, the client may either try another server (perhaps restarting the DHCP server discovery process) or use the Information-request message to obtain other configuration information only."
        },
        {
            "Original": "When the client receives a Reply message in response to a Renew or Rebind message, the client: \\- Sends a Request message to the server that responded if any of the IAs in the Reply message contain the NoBinding status code.",
            "Adjusted": "When the client receives a Reply message in response to a Renew or Rebind message, the client: - Sends a Request message to the server that responded if any of the Identity Associations in the Reply message contain the NoBinding status code."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client places IA options in this message for all IAs.",
            "Adjusted": "The client places IA options in this message for all Identity Associations."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client continues to use other bindings for which the server did not return an error.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- Sends a Renew/Rebind if any of the IAs are not in the Reply message, but as this likely indicates that the server that responded does not support that IA type, sending immediately is unlikely to produce a different result.",
            "Adjusted": "- Sends a Renew/Rebind if any of the Identity Associations are not in the Reply message, but as this likely indicates that the server that responded does not support that IA type, sending immediately is unlikely to produce a different result."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Therefore, the client MUST rate-limit its transmissions (see Section 14.1) and MAY just wait for the normal retransmission time (as if the Reply message had not been received).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client continues to use other bindings for which the server did return information.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- Otherwise accepts the information in the IA.",
            "Adjusted": "- Otherwise accepts the information in the Identity Association."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Whenever a client restarts the DHCP server discovery process or selects an alternate server as described in Section 18.2.9, the client SHOULD stop using all the addresses and delegated prefixes for which it has bindings and try to obtain all required leases from the new server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This facilitates the client using a single state machine for all bindings.",
            "Adjusted": "This approach facilitates the client using a single state machine for all bindings."
        }
    ]
}

20. Authentication of DHCP Messages -> 2:
{
    "20. Authentication of DHCP Messages -> 20.4. Reconfiguration Key Authentication Protocol (RKAP) -> 20.4.3. Client Considerations for RKAP": [
        {
            "Original": "The client will receive a reconfigure key from the server in an Authentication option (seeSection 21.11) in the initial Reply message from the server.",
            "Adjusted": "The client will receive a reconfigure key from the server in an Authentication option (see Section 21.11) in the initial Reply message from the server."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client records the reconfigure key for use in authenticating subsequent Reconfigure messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "To authenticate a Reconfigure message, the client computes an HMAC-MD5 over the Reconfigure message, with zeroes substituted for the HMAC-MD5 field, using the reconfigure key received from the server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If this computed HMAC-MD5 matches the value in the Authentication option, the client accepts the Reconfigure message.",
            "Adjusted": "If the computed HMAC-MD5 matches the value in the Authentication option, the client accepts the Reconfigure message."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "20. Authentication of DHCP Messages -> 20.4. Reconfiguration Key Authentication Protocol (RKAP)": [
        {
            "Original": "RKAP provides protection against misconfiguration of a client caused by a Reconfigure message sent by a malicious DHCP server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In this protocol, a DHCP server sends a reconfigure key to the client in the initial exchange of DHCP messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client records the reconfigure key for use in authenticating subsequent Reconfigure messages from that server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server then includes a Hashed Message Authentication Code (HMAC) computed from the reconfigure key in subsequent Reconfigure messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Both the reconfigure key sent from the server to the client and the HMAC in subsequent Reconfigure messages are carried as the authentication information in an Authentication option (seeSection 21.11).",
            "Adjusted": "Both the reconfigure key sent from the server to the client and the HMAC in subsequent Reconfigure messages are carried as the authentication information in an Authentication option (see Section 21.11)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The format of the authentication information is defined in the following section.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "RKAP is used (initiated by the server) only if the client and server have negotiated to use Reconfigure messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "20.4.2. Server Considerations for RKAP": [
        {
            "Original": "The server selects a reconfigure key for a client during the Request/Reply, Solicit/Reply, or Information-request/Reply message exchange.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server records the reconfigure key and transmits that key to the client in an Authentication option (seeSection 21.11) in the Reply message.",
            "Adjusted": "The server records the reconfigure key and transmits the reconfigure key to the client in an Authentication option (see Section 21.11) in the Reply message."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The reconfigure key is 128 bits long and MUST be a cryptographically strong random or pseudorandom number that cannot easily be predicted.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "To provide authentication for a Reconfigure message, the server selects a replay detection value according to the RDM selected by the server and computes an HMAC-MD5 of the Reconfigure message using the reconfigure key for the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server computes the HMAC-MD5 over the entire DHCP Reconfigure message, including the Authentication option; the HMAC-MD5 field in the Authentication option is set to 0 for the HMAC-MD5 computation.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server includes the HMAC-MD5 in the authentication information field in an Authentication option included in the Reconfigure message sent to the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "20. Authentication of DHCP Messages -> 20.3. Replay Detection": [
        {
            "Original": "The RDM field of the Authentication option (seeSection 21.11) determines the type of replay detection used in the replay detection field.",
            "Adjusted": "The RDM field of the Authentication option (see Section 21.11) determines the type of replay detection used in the replay detection field."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the RDM field contains 0x00, the replay detection field MUST be set to the value of a strictly monotonically increasing 64-bit unsigned integer (modulo 2^64).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Using this technique can reduce the danger of replay attacks.",
            "Adjusted": "Using the strictly monotonically increasing 64-bit unsigned integer technique can reduce the danger of replay attacks."
        },
        {
            "Original": "This method MUST be supported by all Authentication option protocols.",
            "Adjusted": "The strictly monotonically increasing 64-bit unsigned integer method MUST be supported by all Authentication option protocols."
        },
        {
            "Original": "One choice might be to use the 64-bit NTP timestamp format [RFC5905]).",
            "Adjusted": "One choice might be to use the 64-bit NTP timestamp format [RFC5905]."
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client that receives a message with the RDM field set to 0x00 MUST compare its replay detection field with the previous value sent by that same server (based on the Server Identifier option; see Section 21.3) and only accept the message if the received value is greater and record this as the new value.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If this is the first time a client processes an Authentication option sent by a server, the client MUST record the replay detection value and skip the replay detection check.",
            "Adjusted": "If this is the first time a client processes an Authentication option sent by a server, the client MUST record the replay detection value and skip the replay detection check."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Servers that support the reconfigure mechanism MUST ensure that the replay detection value is retained between restarts.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Failing to do so may cause clients to refuse Reconfigure messages sent by the server, effectively rendering the reconfigure mechanism useless.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

19. Relay Agent Behavior -> 19.3. Constr:
{
    "19. Relay Agent Behavior -> 19.3. Construction of Relay-reply Messages": [
        {
            "Original": "A server uses a Relay-reply message to (1) return a response to a client if the original message from the client was relayed to the server in a Relay-forward message or (2) send a Reconfigure message to a client if the server does not have an address it can use to send the message directly to the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A response to the client MUST be relayed through the same relay agents as the original client message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server causes this to happen by creating a Relay-reply message that includes a Relay Message option (seeSection 21.10) containing the message for the next relay agent in the return path to the client.",
            "Adjusted": "The server causes the response to be relayed through the same relay agents by creating a Relay-reply message that includes a Relay Message option (see Section 21.10) containing the message for the next relay agent in the return path to the client."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The contained Relay-reply message contains another Relay Message option to be sent to the next relay agent, and so on.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server must record the contents of the peer-address fields in the received message so it can construct the appropriate Relay-reply message carrying the response from the server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For example, if client C sent a message that was relayed by relay agent A to relay agent B and then to the server, the server would send the following Relay-reply message to relay agent B: msg-type: RELAY-REPL hop-count: 1 link-address: 0 peer-address: A Relay Message option containing the following: msg-type: RELAY-REPL hop-count: 0 link-address: address from link to which C is attached peer-address: C Relay Message option: <response from server> Figure 10: Relay-reply Example When sending a Reconfigure message to a client through a relay agent, the server creates a Relay-reply message that includes a Relay Message option containing the Reconfigure message for the next relay agent in the return path to the client.",
            "Adjusted": "For example, if client C sent a message that was relayed by relay agent A to relay agent B and then to the server, the server would send the following Relay-reply message to relay agent B: msg-type: RELAY-REPL hop-count: 1 link-address: 0 peer-address: A Relay Message option containing the following: msg-type: RELAY-REPL hop-count: 0 link-address: address from link to which C is attached peer-address: C Relay Message option: response from server. When sending a Reconfigure message to a client through a relay agent, the server creates a Relay-reply message that includes a Relay Message option containing the Reconfigure message for the next relay agent in the return path to the client."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server sets the peer-address field in the Relay-reply message header to the address of the client and sets the link-address field as required by the relay agent to relay the Reconfigure message to the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server obtains the addresses of the client and the relay agent through prior interaction with the client or through some external mechanism.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

