            "Original": "T2 The time interval after which the client should contact any available server to extend the lifetimes of the addresses assigned to the IA_NA; T2 is a time duration relative to the current time expressed in units of seconds.",
            "Adjusted": "T2 is the time interval after which the client should contact any available server to extend the lifetimes of the addresses assigned to the IA_NA; T2 is a time duration relative to the current time expressed in units of seconds."
        },
        {
            "Original": "A 4-octet field containing an unsigned integer.",
            "Adjusted": "T2 is a 4-octet field containing an unsigned integer."
        },
        {
            "Original": "IA_NA-options Options associated with this IA_NA.",
            "Adjusted": "The IA_NA-options field contains options associated with this IA_NA."
        },
        {
            "Original": "A variable-length field (12 octets less than the value in the option-len field).",
            "Adjusted": "The IA_NA-options field is a variable-length field that is 12 octets less than the value in the option-len field."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The IA_NA-options field encapsulates those options that are specific to this IA_NA.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For example, all of the IA Address options (see Section 21.6) carrying the addresses associated with this IA_NA are in the IA_NA-options field.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Each IA_NA carries one \"set\" of non-temporary addresses; it is up to the server policy to determine how many addresses are assigned, but typically at most one address is assigned from each prefix assigned to the link to which the client is attached.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "An IA_NA option may only appear in the options area of a DHCP message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A DHCP message may contain multiple IA_NA options (though each must have a unique IAID).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The status of any operations involving this IA_NA is indicated in a Status Code option (see Section 21.13) in the IA_NA-options field.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that an IA_NA has no explicit \"lifetime\" or \"lease length\" of its own.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "When the valid lifetimes of all of the addresses in an IA_NA have expired, the IA_NA can be considered as having expired.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "T1 and T2 are included to give servers explicit control over when a client recontacts the server about a specific IA_NA.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In a message sent by a client to a server, the T1 and T2 fields SHOULD be set to 0.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MUST ignore any values in these fields in messages received from a client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In a message sent by a server to a client, the client MUST use the values in the T1 and T2 fields for the T1 and T2 times, unless values in those fields are 0.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The values in the T1 and T2 fields are the number of seconds until T1 and T2 and are calculated since reception of the message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "As per Section 7.7, the value 0xffffffff is taken to mean \"infinity\" and should be used carefully.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server selects the T1 and T2 values to allow the client to extend the lifetimes of any addresses in the IA_NA before the lifetimes expire, even if the server is unavailable for some short period of time.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Recommended values for T1 and T2 are 0.5 and 0.8 times the shortest preferred lifetime of the addresses in the IA that the server is willing to extend, respectively.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the \"shortest\" preferred lifetime is 0xffffffff (\"infinity\"), the recommended T1 and T2 values are also 0xffffffff.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the time at which the addresses in an IA_NA are to be renewed is to be left to the discretion of the client, the server sets the T1 and T2 values to 0.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client MUST follow the rules defined in Section 14.2.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If a client receives an IA_NA with T1 greater than T2 and both T1 and T2 are greater than 0, the client discards the IA_NA option and processes the remainder of the message as though the server had not included the invalid IA_NA option.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

