22. Security Considerations:
{
    "22. Security Considerations": [
        {
            "Original": "This section discusses security considerations that are not related to privacy.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "SeeSection 23 for a discussion dedicated to privacy.",
            "Adjusted": "See Section 23 for a discussion dedicated to privacy."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The threat to DHCP is inherently an insider threat (assuming a properly configured network where DHCP ports are blocked on the perimeter gateways of the enterprise).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Regardless of the gateway configuration, however, the potential attacks by insiders and outsiders are the same.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "DHCP lacks end-to-end encryption between clients and servers; thus, hijacking, tampering, and eavesdropping attacks are all possible as a result.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Some network environments (discussed below) can be secured through various means to minimize these attacks.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "One attack specific to a DHCP client is the establishment of a malicious server with the intent of providing incorrect configuration information to the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The motivation for doing so may be to mount a \"man in the middle\" attack that causes the client to communicate with a malicious server instead of a valid server for some service (such as DNS or NTP).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The malicious server may also mount a DoS attack through misconfiguration of the client; this attack would cause all network communication from the client to fail.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A malicious DHCP server might cause a client to set its SOL_MAX_RT and INF_MAX_RT parameters to an unreasonably high value with the SOL_MAX_RT (see Section 21.24) and INF_MAX_RT (see Section 21.25) options; this may cause an undue delay in a client completing its DHCP protocol transaction in the case where no other valid response is received.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Assuming that the client also receives a response from a valid DHCP server, large values for SOL_MAX_RT and INF_MAX_RT will not have any effect.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A malicious server can also send a Server Unicast option (see Section 21.12) to a client in an Advertise message, thus potentially causing the client to bypass relays and communicate only with the malicious server for subsequent Request and Renew messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Another threat to DHCP clients originates from mistakenly or accidentally configured DHCP servers that answer DHCP client requests with unintentionally incorrect configuration parameters.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A DHCP client may also be subject to attack through the receipt of a Reconfigure message from a malicious server that causes the client to obtain incorrect configuration information from that server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that although a client sends its response (Renew, Rebind, or Information-request message) through a relay agent and, therefore, that response will only be received by servers to which DHCP messages are relayed, a malicious server could send a Reconfigure message to a client, followed (after an appropriate delay) by a Reply message that would be accepted by the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Thus, a malicious server that is not on the network path between the client and the server may still be able to mount a Reconfigure attack on a client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The use of transaction IDs that are cryptographically sound and cannot easily be predicted will also reduce the probability that such an attack will be successful.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Because of the opportunity for attack through the Reconfigure message, a DHCP client MUST discard any Reconfigure message that does not include authentication or that does not pass the validation process for the authentication protocol.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "RKAP, described in Section 20.4, provides protection against the use of a Reconfigure message by a malicious DHCP server to mount a DoS or man-in-the-middle attack on a client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This protocol can be compromised by an attacker that can intercept the initial message in which the DHCP server sends the key \"in plain text\" to the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Many of these attacks by rogue servers can be mitigated by making use of the mechanisms described in [RFC7610] and [RFC7513 Solution for DHCP\"\")].",
            "Adjusted": "Many of these attacks by rogue servers can be mitigated by making use of the mechanisms described in [RFC7610] and [RFC7513]."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The threat specific to a DHCP server is an invalid client masquerading as a valid client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The motivation for this may be for theft of service, or to circumvent auditing for any number of nefarious purposes.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The threat common to both the client and the server is the \"resource- exhaustion\" DoS attack.",
            "Adjusted": "The threat common to both the client and the server is the \"resource-exhaustion\" DoS attack."
        },
        {
            "Original": "These attacks typically involve the exhaustion of available assigned addresses or delegatable prefixes, or the exhaustion of CPU or network bandwidth, and are present any time there is a shared resource.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Some forms of these exhaustion attacks can be partially mitigated by appropriate server policy, e.g., limiting the maximum number of leases any one client can get.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The messages exchanged between relay agents and servers may be used to mount a man-in-the-middle or DoS attack.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Communication between a server and a relay agent, and communication between relay agents, can be authenticated and encrypted through the use of IPsec, as described in [RFC8213].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "However, the use of manually configured pre-shared keys for IPsec between relay agents and servers does not defend against replayed DHCP messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Replayed messages can represent a DoS attack through exhaustion of processing resources but not through misconfiguration or exhaustion of other resources such as assignable addresses and delegatable prefixes.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Various network environments also offer levels of security if deployed as described below.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- In enterprise and factory networks, use of authentication per [IEEE-802.1x] can prevent unknown or untrusted clients from connecting to the network.",
            "Adjusted": "In enterprise and factory networks, use of authentication per [IEEE-802.1x] can prevent unknown or untrusted clients from connecting to the network."
        },
        {
            "Original": "However, this does not necessarily assure that the connected client will be a good DHCP or network actor.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- For wired networks where clients typically are connected to a switch port, snooping DHCP multicast (or unicast) traffic becomes difficult, as the switches limit the traffic delivered to a port.",
            "Adjusted": "For wired networks where clients typically are connected to a switch port, snooping DHCP multicast (or unicast) traffic becomes difficult, as the switches limit the traffic delivered to a port."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client's DHCP multicast packets (with destination address fe02::1:2) are only forwarded to the DHCP server's (or relay's) switch port -- not all ports.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Also, the server's (or relay's) unicast replies are only delivered to the target client's port -- not all ports.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- In public networks (such as a Wi-Fi network in a coffee shop or airport), it is possible for others within radio range to snoop DHCP and other traffic.",
            "Adjusted": "In public networks (such as a Wi-Fi network in a coffee shop or airport), it is possible for others within radio range to snoop DHCP and other traffic."
        },
        {
            "Original": "But in these environments, there is very little if anything that can be learned from the DHCP traffic itself (either from client to server or from server to client) if the privacy considerations provided in Section 23 are followed.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Even for devices that do not follow the privacy considerations, there is little that can be learned that would not be available from subsequent communications anyway (such as the device's Media Access Control (MAC) address).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Also, because all clients will typically receive similar configuration details, a bad actor that initiates a DHCP request itself can learn much of such information.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "As mentioned above, one threat is that the RKAP key for a client can be learned (if the initial Solicit/Advertise/Request/Reply exchange is monitored) and trigger a premature reconfiguration, but this is relatively easily prevented by disallowing direct client-to-client communication on these networks or using [RFC7610] and [RFC7513 Solution for DHCP\"\")].",
            "Adjusted": "As mentioned above, one threat is that the RKAP key for a client can be learned (if the initial Solicit/Advertise/Request/Reply exchange is monitored) and trigger a premature reconfiguration, but this is relatively easily prevented by disallowing direct client-to-client communication on these networks or using [RFC7610] and [RFC7513]."
        }
    ]
}

