        },
        {
            "Original": "Section 4.2 (\"DHCP Terminology\") was expanded to incorporate definitions from RFC 3633, add T1/T2 definitions, add definitions useful in describing combined address assignment and prefix delegation operations, and improve some existing definitions.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "6\\.",
            "Adjusted": "6."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Section 5 (\"Client/Server Exchanges\") was added from material previously in Section 1 of RFC 3315 (\"Introduction and Overview\") and was expanded.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "7\\.",
            "Adjusted": "7."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Section 6 (\"Operational Models\") is new.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "It provides information on the kinds of DHCP clients and how they operate.",
            "Adjusted": "Section 6 provides information on the kinds of DHCP clients and how they operate."
        },
        {
            "Original": "8\\.",
            "Adjusted": "8."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Section 7 (\"DHCP Constants\") was primarily updated to add constants from RFC 4242 and RFC 7083.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that the default HOP_COUNT_LIMIT value was reduced from 32 to 8.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "9\\.",
            "Adjusted": "9."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Sections 8 (\"Client/Server Message Formats\"), 9 (\"Relay Agent/ Server Message Formats\"), and 10 (\"Representation and Use of Domain Names\") had only very minor changes.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "10\\.",
            "Adjusted": "10."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Section 11 (\"DHCP Unique Identifier (DUID)\") now discourages, rather than disallows, a server to parse the DUID; now includes some information on the DUID-UUID (RFC 6355); and had other minor edits.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "11\\.",
            "Adjusted": "11."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Section 12 (\"Identity Association\") was expanded to better explain the concept and to also include prefix delegation.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "12\\.",
            "Adjusted": "12."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Section 13 (\"Assignment to an IA\") incorporates material from two sections (11 and 12) of RFC 3315 and also includes a section on prefix delegation.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "13\\.",
            "Adjusted": "13."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Section 14 (\"Transmission of Messages by a Client\") was expanded to include rate limiting by clients and how clients should handle T1 or T2 values of 0.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "14\\.",
            "Adjusted": "14."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Section 15 (\"Reliability of Client-Initiated Message Exchanges\") was expanded to clarify that the Elapsed Time option must be updated in retransmitted messages and that a client is not required to listen for DHCP traffic for the entire retransmission period.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "15\\.",
            "Adjusted": "15."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Section 16 (\"Message Validation\") had minor edits.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "16\\.",
            "Adjusted": "16."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Section 17 (\"Client Source Address and Interface Selection\") was expanded to include prefix delegation.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "17\\.",
            "Adjusted": "17."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Section 18 (\"DHCP Configuration Exchanges\") consolidates what used to be in the following sections in RFC 3315: \"DHCP Server Solicitation\" (Section 17), \"DHCP Client-Initiated Configuration Exchange\" (Section 18), and \"DHCP Server-Initiated Configuration Exchange\" (Section 19).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This material was reorganized and enhanced, and it incorporates prefix delegation from RFC 3633 and other changes from RFC 4242, RFC 7083, and RFC 7550.",
            "Adjusted": "The material in Section 18 was reorganized and enhanced, and it incorporates prefix delegation from RFC 3633 and other changes from RFC 4242, RFC 7083, and RFC 7550."
        },
        {
            "Original": "A few changes of note: A.",
            "Adjusted": "A few changes of note: A."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Option Request option is no longer optional for some messages (Solicit and Information-request), as RFC 7083 requires clients to request SOL_MAX_RT or INF_MAX_RT options.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "B.",
            "Adjusted": "B."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Reconfigure message should no longer contain IA_NA/IA_PD, ORO, or other options to indicate to the client what was reconfigured.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client should request everything it needs in the response to the Reconfigure.",
            "Adjusted": "The client should request everything the client needs in the response to the Reconfigure message."
        },
        {
            "Original": "C.",
            "Adjusted": "C."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The lifetime and T1/T2 hints should not be sent by a client (it should send values of 0 in these fields), and any non-zero values should be ignored by the server.",
            "Adjusted": "The lifetime and T1/T2 hints should not be sent by a client (the client should send values of 0 in these fields), and any non-zero values should be ignored by the server."
        },
        {
            "Original": "D.",
            "Adjusted": "D."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Clarified that a server may return different addresses in the Reply than requested by a client in the Request message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Also clarified that a server must not include addresses that it will not assign.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Also, Section 18.2.12 (\"Refreshing Configuration Information\") was added to indicate use cases for when a client should try to refresh network information.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "18\\.",
            "Adjusted": "18."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Section 19 (\"Relay Agent Behavior\") incorporates RFC 7283 and had minor edits.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A new section, \"Interaction between Relay Agents and Servers\" (Section 19.4), was added.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "19\\.",
            "Adjusted": "19."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Section 20 (\"Authentication of DHCP Messages\") includes significant changes: IPsec materials were mostly removed and replaced with a reference to RFC 8213, and the delayed authentication protocol has been obsoleted (see Section 25).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that RKAP is still considered current.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "20\\.",
            "Adjusted": "20."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Section 21 (\"DHCP Options\") was expanded to incorporate OPTION_IA_PD and OPTION_IAPREFIX from RFC 3633, the Information Refresh Time option (OPTION_INFORMATION_REFRESH_TIME) from RFC 4242, and the SOL_MAX_RT and INF_MAX_RT options from RFC 7083.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Some additional edits were made to clarify option handling, such as which options should not be in an Option Request option.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "21\\.",
            "Adjusted": "21."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The security considerations (Section 22) were updated to expand the discussion of security threats and include material from the incorporated documents, primarily RFC 3633.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "22\\.",
            "Adjusted": "22."
        },
        {
            "Original": "New privacy considerations were added (Section 23) to account for privacy issues.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "23\\.",
            "Adjusted": "23."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Section 24 (\"IANA Considerations\") was rewritten to reflect the changes requested for this document, as other documents have already made the message, option, DUID, and status code assignments and this document does not add any new assignments.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "24\\.",
            "Adjusted": "24."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Section 25 (\"Obsoleted Mechanisms\") is a new section that documents the mechanisms obsoleted by this specification.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "25\\.",
            "Adjusted": "25."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Appendices B (\"Appearance of Options in Message Types\") and C (\"Appearance of Options in the \"options\" Field of DHCP Options\") were updated to reflect the incorporated options from RFC 3633, RFC 4242, and RFC 7083.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "26\\.",
            "Adjusted": "26."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Where appropriate, informative references have been added to provide further background and guidance throughout the document (as can be noted by the vast increase in references).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "27\\.",
            "Adjusted": "27."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Changes were made to incorporate the following errata for RFC 3315: Erratum IDs 294, 295, 1373, 1815, 2471, 2472, 2509, 2928, 3577, 5450; RFC 3633: Erratum IDs 248, 2468, 2469, 2470, 3736; and RFC 3736: Erratum ID 3796.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that Erratum ID 1880 for RFC 3633 no longer applies, as servers (delegating routers) ignore received T1/T2 hints (see (C) in item 17 above).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "28\\.",
            "Adjusted": "28."
        },
        {
            "Original": "General changes to other IPv6 specifications, such as removing the use of site-local unicast addresses and adding unique local addresses, were made to the document.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "29\\.",
            "Adjusted": "29."
        },
        {
            "Original": "It should be noted that this document does not refer to all DHCPv6 functionality and specifications.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Readers of this specification should visit <https://www.iana.org/assignments/ dhcpv6-parameters> and <<https://datatracker.ietf.org/wg/dhc/>> to learn of the RFCs that define DHCPv6 messages, options, status codes, and more.",
            "Adjusted": "Readers of this specification should visit https://www.iana.org/assignments/dhcpv6-parameters and https://datatracker.ietf.org/wg/dhc/ to learn of the RFCs that define DHCPv6 messages, options, status codes, and more."
        }
    ]
}

